sect1.para:
      There is something else to note about what Hack doesn't support: top-level code. This may be surprising, but the Hack type checker wants everything in a class or function (global scope static analysis can prove to be very difficult). The implication here is that the Hack type checker will ignore any top-level code when in partial or decl modes, and actually throw an error in strict mode. For example:



<?hh // strict

// Top-level code is not supported in Hack
// It is ignored in partial and decl modes
// And a type checker error is thrown in strict mode
for ($i=1; $i<=5; $i++)
{
  echo "The number is " . $i . "\n";
}


        &example.outputs;


File "/tmp/topCode.php", line 6, characters 1-3:
Remove all toplevel statements except for requires




          As with many cases in Hack, the above code will run in HHVM just fine. So typing hhvm topCode.php will run correctly. The code just will not be type checked.

      Unlike PHP, Hack does not allow one to define a function on a class that collides with the class name. For example, this is acceptable in PHP:



<?php
class Foo {
  public function foo() {}
}




          However, this is not acceptable in Hack:



<?hh
class Foo {
  public function foo() {}
}


        &example.outputs;


File "c.php", line 3, characters 21-29:
This is a dangerous method name, if you want to define a constructor, use __construct

      The reason for Hack disallowing this comes down to constructors. In the above example, foo() behaves like a constructor and gets called upon instantiation using new Foo(). This could be very confusing especially when there is an explicit constructor as well.



<?hh
class Foo {
  // 2 constructors?
  public function __construct() {}
  public function foo() {}
}

      PHP allows children to call static methods in the parent. For example:



<?php
class StaticFoo {
  public static function staticMethod() {
    return "Hello";
  }
}

class StaticBar extends StaticFoo {
  public function fooStatic() {
    return parent::staticMethod();
  }
}




          Hack does not currently allow this. The following error will be displayed:

        &example.outputs;


